324026.summary:
About Health Canada
Health Canada is the federal department responsible for helping protect the Canadian public by researching, assessing and collaborating in the management of the health risks and safety hazards associated with the many consumer products that Canadians use every day. Health Canada conducts tests and research on consumer products,
supports the development of safety standards and guidelines, enforces legislation by conducting investigations, inspections, seizures and prosecutions, publishes product advisories, warnings and recalls and promotes safety and the responsible use of products. Health Canada's goal is for Canada to be among the countries with the healthiest and safest people in the world.
Under the Canada Consumer Product Safety Act (http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-1.68/page-1.html), industry is responsible for the safety of consumer products and is obligated to report to Health Canada when they become aware of a potential danger to human health and safety. The students will review incoming cases from the industry and the consumers alike. Subsequently, they will assist in identifying any potential hazards related to consumer electrical products by analyzing and conducting research.
The Risk Assessment Bureau Electrical Unit of the Consumer Product Safety Program at Health Canada:
Assesses/evaluates incoming electrical product incident reports from across the country;
Assesses/evaluates root cause analyses reports;
Performs Risk Characterization where a level of risk is determined;
Supports the Risk Management Bureau in their effort to issue public advisories or issue product recalls;
Works with all levels of Governmental agencies, the industry, the Canadian public, as well as regional, national, and international groups to improve on the safety of electrical consumer products;
Contributes to the improvement of existing regulations and standards or development of new ones; and
Participates on standard development organizations technical committees.

